Transform the Data in Power BI using Query Editor 2

To make our data better fit our needs, we need to perform several transformations using the Query Editor in Power BI.

Here are the steps we need for our report:

1. The data source file name is too long. Lets rename it to TopDiagnosis. In Power Query Editor, click the data table and choose "Rename". Chose TopDiagnosis


2. Split Column: DRG Definition

We want to split the number code associated with each diagnosis and move both into separate columns. We do this by using marking the column and then using Split Column function. In Split Column chose use delimiter. Choose Custom and specify where we want to split ( '-' ) and chose left most delimiter.


Lets rename these new columns for better usability. Right click on the column title and choose "Rename". Rename the numbers to DRG Numbers and remove the ".2" from the Definition.


Now we are done transforming the data, and we now need to create additional calculation and measures:  In Query Editor -  Click Close and Apply. 


3. Now we want to add some calculated columns and measure to help with our visualizations.

Go to Data tab and Modeling to access New Measure and Column


Create Calculated Columns and Measures:

1. Create a new Calculated Column: Average Patient out of Pocket

    Average Patient Out of Pocket = TopDiagnosis[ Average Total Payments ]-TopDiagnosis[Average Medicare Payments]

2. Create a new Calculated Column: Charges minus Payment

    Charges minus Payment = TopDiagnosis[ Average Covered Charges ]-TopDiagnosis[ Average Total Payments ]

3. Create a new Measure: Charges vs Payments %

    Charges Paid % = SUM(TopDiagnosis[ Average Total Payments ]) / SUM(TopDiagnosis[ Average Covered Charges ])

4. Create a new Calculated Column: Charges paid no filter

    Charges paid no filter = CALCULATE(SUM(TopDiagnosis[ Average Covered Charges ]),ALL(TopDiagnosis[Provider State]))

5. Create a new Measure: State vs US

  State vs US = SUM(TopDiagnosis[ Average Covered Charges ])/CALCULATE(SUM(TopDiagnosis[ Average Covered Charges ]),ALL(TopDiagnosis[Provider State]))

Understanding the difference between Calculated Column and Measure in Power BI/DAX
